===Legacy===
In 2000, ''Rio'' was ranked #98 in Q magazine's "100 Greatest British Albums". In 2003, it was listed at #65 in the NME "100 Greatest Albums of All Time". In 2004, CMJ ranked it as #1 in their "Top 20 Most-Played Albums of 1982". In 2008 it was ranked 24th best British album of all time in a joint HMV Q poll.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wordmagazine.co.uk/content/top-50-british-albums-poll |title=Top 50 British albums poll |publisher=Word Magazine |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080221185149/http://www.wordmagazine.co.uk/content/top-50-british-albums-poll |archivedate=2008-02-21 |accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref> It ranked #95 in [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Top 100 Albums of the 1980s,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/features/staff-lists/5882-top-100-albums-of-the-1980s/|title=Staff Lists: Top 100 Albums of the 1980s |date=20 November 2002|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=23 February 2013}}</ref> and is included in the list ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/1001Albums.htm|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear - 2008 Edition|publisher=Rocklistmusic.co.uk|accessdate=23 February 2013}}</ref> In April 2013 Rio was voted number 3 in BBC Radio 2's Top 100 Favourite Albums of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rlpnc/live|title=Top 100 Favourite Album Countdown - Live Updates|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2013-09-16}}</ref>

Three decades later, [[John Taylor (bass guitarist)|John Taylor]] still held the album in high regard. "The writing on ''Rio'' is fantastic, all out. Essential Duran Duran," he recalled in his 2012 memoir, ''In the Pleasure Groove''. He also had high praise for the band's musicianship. "Every one of us is performing ... at the absolute peak of our talents," he wrote. "There is no showboating. Every part is thoughtful, considered, part of a greater whole."<ref>{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=John|title=In the Pleasure Groove: Love, Death & Duran Duran|year=2012|publisher=Sphere|location=London|isbn=9780751549041|authorlink=John Taylor (bass guitarist)|page=178}}</ref>

In 2013 science-fiction movie ''[[Oblivion_(2013_film)|Oblivion]]'', in an apocalyptic world, a copy of Duran Duran's "Rio" can be seen briefly in a scene where Tom Cruise's character browses his old vinyl records collection, as part of the remnants of some better times for human civilization.

